    <abstract>
      <t>This document defines the Metadata-Filter (MF) Subsequent Address Family Identifier (SAFI). A BGP speaker uses MF to signal its interest or non-interest in receiving service metadata attributes (e.g., the 5G Edge Metadata Path Attribute) on routes that carry specified Route Targets (RTs), while leaving reachability unchanged. The mechanism targets iBGP topologies with Route Reflectors (RRs). It follows the RTC (RFC4684) operational model but applies it to service metadata, rather than NLRI distribution, to reduce UPDATE size and control-plane churn.
		</t>
    </abstract>

    <note title="Requirements Language">
      <t>The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT",
      "SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this
      document are to be interpreted as described in <xref
      target="RFC2119"></xref> <xref target="RFC8174"></xref>
      when, and only when, they appear in all
      capitals, as shown here.</t>
    </note>
  </front>

  <middle>
    <section title="Introduction">
      <t>Emerging deployments (e.g., the IETF CATS effort) can attach compute/capacity-related service metadata to routes—such as latency, load, CPU/GPU availability, and queue depth—for ingress nodes to select optimal paths not only based on network distance but also the service enviroment for the ultra-low latencey services. These attributes can proliferate per service and churn rapidly. In many 5G networks, ingress nodes (UPFs or adjacent PEs) have constrained control-plane resources, and most UE sessions they anchor are not ultra-low-latency; they neither need nor can efficiently process large, fast-changing metadata on every route. Indiscriminate distribution inflates UPDATE size, increases RR/PE CPU and memory consumption, and can slow convergence under churn.</t>
	  
	  <t>In typical iBGP topologies with Route Reflectors, data-center/edge nodes can advertise routes with service metadata toward the RR without knowing which ingress peers will use them. Receivers therefore need a way to decline metadata for uninterested classes while continuing to receive reachability. The Metadata-Filter (MF) SAFI provides this: a receiver signals its interest or non-interest in service metadata for routes that carry specified Route Targets (RTs); the RR installs standing policy for that peer and omits service metadata on matching advertisements, leaving route distribution unchanged and advertisements to other peers unaffected.</t>

	  <t>Importantly for 5G deployments, a UPF’s interest in metadata is dynamic. When Ultra-Low Latency services/UEs roam out of the UPF’s serving range (and are no longer anchored there), the UPF can advertise MF entries for the corresponding service class RT to suppress receipt of metadata; when those services return, the UPF withdraws the MF entries to resume receiving metadata. MF thus lets ingress nodes adjust metadata delivery as service placement and UE anchoring change, while keeping reachability intact.</t>

   </section>

